Converting all the date time objects to datetime format

In [6]:
df['when_the_delivery_started'] =  pd.to_datetime(df['when_the_delivery_started'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff'] = pd.to_datetime(df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup'] = pd.to_datetime(df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
df['when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup'] = pd.to_datetime(df['when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
df['how_long_it_took_to_order']  = pd.to_datetime(df['how_long_it_took_to_order'], format='%H:%M:%S.%f')

Data Integrity Issues¶

In this section we investigate the data integrity issues.

Issue 1¶

We first start out by looking at the missing values.

From the above results we can see that most of the NA values are occurring in the 'how_long_it_took_to_order' column. This metric gives us an important estimate about how long the users generally take to order from Jumpman23. With nearly half of the values missing, we cannot use this column to perform any analysis.

In [9]:
df['how_long_it_took_to_order'].min()
Out[9]:
Timestamp('1900-01-01 00:01:22.997519')

On investigating this column further, we see that the minimum timestamp is of the year 1900. Hence we need to make sure we are collecting the data for this particular column properly. Also, most of the NA values are occuring in timestamp events which is another area to look into and understand the reasons behind the erroneous entries.

Issue 2¶

Checking if the event times recorded have any inconsistencies

In [10]:
inconsistent_delivery_started_gt_arrived_pickup_df= df[df.when_the_delivery_started > df.when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_pickup]
len(inconsistent_delivery_started_gt_arrived_pickup_df)
Out[10]:
501

In the above code, we can see that there are 501 data records where the time when delivery was started is greater than the time Jumpman arrived at the pickup place. This is another data integrity issue as the time when the delivery was started always has to be less than the time the Jumpman arrived at the pickup place.

In [11]:
inconsistent_arrived_pickup_gt_left_pickup_df= df[df.when_the_delivery_started > df.when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup]
len(inconsistent_arrived_pickup_gt_left_pickup_df)
Out[11]:
2

In the above code, we can see that there are 2 data records where the time when delivery was started is greater than the time Jumpman left the pickup place.

Issue 3¶

Checking for duplicate rows

In [12]:
inconsistent_duplicate_data = df[df.duplicated(subset=None, keep='first')]
len(inconsistent_duplicate_data)
Out[12]:
16

From the above result, we can observe that there are 16 records where all the values are duplicated.

When we drill down a bit deeper into this problem, we observe that if a user wants to order the same item more than once, a new data record is getting created for it instead of only the item_quantity getting updated.

We observe that there are a few items who appear under different item categories. This categories might be dependant on the pickup places but if not then it would be easier for us to understand how the ordering trend is if we could group them under just one category.

Issue 5¶

Another issue which we observe in one of the graphs below is that the pickup categories could be defined clearly. We can see Burger as a dominant category which the customers order but it can be included under American. By doing this, American would be the most preferred pickup category.

Defining the item categories and pickup categories clearly and removing the current ambiguity would help us to understand how we are performing in this new market.

How many items are the customers ordering at once¶

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))

ax = sns.countplot(x="item_quantity", data=df, palette="Blues_d", order = df.item_quantity.value_counts().index)

ax.grid(False)
plt.title('Quantity of items ordered the most', fontsize = 20.5)
plt.xlabel('Count of Items', fontsize = 17.5)
plt.ylabel('Quantity', fontsize = 17.5)

for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate('{:}'.format(p.get_height()),(p.get_x()+0.3, p.get_height()+50), fontsize = 15)

We can see that generally at once, the customers order just 1 item. But, we should also note that in a few cases a customer is ordering more than one item at the same time but the data gets recorded differently. This is one of the issues covered in the data integrity issues section.

How long it takes for the order to be completed?¶

Here we are considering the time when the delivery is started to the time when the Jumpman reach the dropoff location

In [22]:
df['time_from_order_to_dropoff'] = df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff'] - df['when_the_delivery_started']
In [23]:
df['time_from_order_to_dropoff'] = df['time_from_order_to_dropoff'].dt.seconds/(60)
In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize=(40, 14))
ax = plt.hist(df.time_from_order_to_dropoff, bins=50)

plt.title('Histogram of total delivery times', fontsize = 45)
plt.xlabel('Total Delivery Time (In Minutes)', fontsize = 35)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize = 35)

plt.xticks(np.arange(0.0, float(int(max(df.time_from_order_to_dropoff)) + 1.0), 25 ))
plt.yticks(np.arange(0.0, 1100, 100 ))
plt.tick_params(axis='x', which='minor')

We can see that most the delivery times range between 25 to 50 minutes

How long it takes for the Jumpman to reach the dropoff location?¶

Here we are considering the time when the Jumpman leaves the pickup location to the time when the Jumpman reach the dropoff location

In [25]:
df['time_when_jumpman_started_with_delivery'] = df['when_the_Jumpman_arrived_at_dropoff'] - df['when_the_Jumpman_left_pickup']
In [26]:
df['time_when_jumpman_started_with_delivery'] = df['time_when_jumpman_started_with_delivery'].dt.seconds/(60)
In [27]:
tmp3 = df['time_when_jumpman_started_with_delivery'].dropna()
In [28]:
plt.figure(figsize=(40, 14))
ax = plt.hist(tmp3, bins=50)

plt.title('Histogram of time taken by Jumpman to deliver the order', fontsize = 45)
plt.xlabel('Time taken to deliver by Jumpman (In Minutes)', fontsize = 35)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize = 35)

plt.xticks(np.arange(0.0, float(int(max(tmp3))+1.0), 10 ))
plt.yticks(np.arange(0.0, 1000, 100 ))
plt.tick_params(axis='x', which='minor')

We can observe that majority of deliveries are completed in 10 minutes once the jumpman has left the pickup place
